{
  "answer": "**Chapter 89 of the *Viṣṇu Smṛti*** is titled simply \"Chapter 89\" (like all chapters in this work), but its content concerns purification rituals (*vratas*) observed during the sacred month of *Kārttika* (कार्तिक), which is dedicated to the deity Agni (the fire god, described as \"the mouth of all the gods\").[^1]\n\nIt prescribes practices such as daily bathing outside (with subdued senses), muttering the Gāyatrī mantra (or prayers), and eating sacrificial food (*havis*) only once a day. These observances are said to purify a person from all sins committed over a year—or even all sins if performed throughout the month with self-control.[^2][^3]\n\n[^1]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, [Chapter 89](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/89/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, [Chapter 89, ¶1-3](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/89/translation/#p-c3a34c).\n\n[^3]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, [Chapter 89, ¶4](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/89/translation/#p-405f67).",
